# Version bumps (semver)

Release id lives in repo-root **`VERSION`** and must stay in lockstep with **`package.json`** `"version"` (`npm run check:version` enforces this). When a task warrants a version change, update **both** to the same value in the same commit.

Use [semantic versioning](https://semver.org/): **`MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH`** (e.g. `1.4.2`).

## Which digit to bump

| Change type | Bump | Reset | Examples |
|-------------|------|-------|----------|
| **Patch** | `x.y.(z+1)` | — | Bug fixes, regressions, small behavior corrections, safe refactors, copy/style tweaks, test-only changes that do not add user-facing capability. |
| **Minor** | `x.(y+1).0` | PATCH → `0` | New features, new UI or gameplay capability, backwards-compatible protocol/schema additions, new optional settings. |
| **Major** | `(x+1).0.0` | MINOR/PATCH → `0` | Breaking changes: removed or renamed client/server message fields, incompatible save/session format, intentional removal of behavior users relied on. |

## Heuristics for this project

- **Patch** if players/ops would describe it as “fix” or “adjust” and nothing new is advertised.
- **Minor** if you would mention it in release notes as a **new** thing users can try.
- **Major** if existing clients or sessions could **break** against the same server/build without coordinated upgrade.

If the work is **docs-only**, **internal refactor with no release**, or the user said **not** to version: leave **`VERSION`** / **`package.json`** unchanged unless they explicitly asked for a bump.

## After editing versions

Run `npm run check:version` (or `npm run smoke:ci`) before finishing so CI will not fail on mismatch.
